  <section1 id="sFocus">
	 <secTitle>Topic and Focus Constructions</secTitle>
	<p><content>
This section considers two types of constructions which draw attention to a particular element.  Since topics occur outside of focus constructions, they will be considered first.  The following example shows that a single sentence may have both a topic and a focused phrase.  In this case, the topic </content><langData>Bill</langData><content> is introduced by the topic marker </content><langData>as for</langData><content>, then the focused phrase </content><langData>soccer</langData><content>, which has been moved out of its regular place in the sentence follows.</content></p>
<ul>
<li>
<content>As for Bill, soccer he plays __ best.</content>
</li></ul>
<section2 id="sFocusTopics">
	<secTitle>Topics and Topic Markers</secTitle>
<p><content>
As defined here, topic constructions consist of a topic phrase followed by a complete sentence or question and usually set apart by punctuation.  Certain markers may be used to set off topics, as shown in the following English examples: </content>
   <langData>As for John, I think he will make a good doctor</langData><content> and </content><langData>Speaking of Jill, where is she?</langData>    </p>

<p show="swTopicNo"><langName/><content> does not allow topic phrases. </content></p>
<p show="swTopicYes"><langName/><content> has topic phrases which occur </content>
			<case element="focus" attr="topicPos">
				<caseText value="before">before</caseText>
				<caseText value="after">after</caseText>
				<caseText value="unknown">_______</caseText>
			</case>
			<content> the main sentence or question.   Some examples include:</content>
</p>
			<example show="swTopicYes">
				<interlinear exampleLoc="focus/topicExample"/>
			</example>
   <p show="swTopicYes"><content>As the examples show, the topic phrase in </content><langName/><content> is </content>
<case element="focus" attr="topicMarker">
<caseText value="no">not marked by a topic marker.  Only the position in the sentence and possibly punctuation distinguish the topic phrase.</caseText>
<caseText value="yesWord">marked by certain words or phrases.</caseText>
<caseText value="yesClitic">marked by one or more clitics which attach to the topic phrase.</caseText>
<caseText value="yesAffix">marked by one or more affixes which attach to the topic phrase.</caseText>
</case>
<text show="swTopicYesWord"><content>The topic markers occur </content>
<case element="focus" attr="topicMarkerPos">
<caseText value="before">before the topic phrase itself.</caseText>
<caseText value="after">after the topic phrase itself.</caseText>
<caseText value="either">on either side of the topic phrase itself, but not on both sides in the same sentence.</caseText>
<caseText value="both">on both sides of the topic phrase itself.</caseText>
<caseText value="unknown">_______.</caseText>
</case>
<content> A topic marker is </content><case element="focus" attr="topicMarkerRequired">
<caseText value="no">optional</caseText>
<caseText value="yes">required</caseText></case>
<content> whenever there is a topic phrase.</content>
</text>
<text show="swTopicYesWordEitherNo"><content> There are separate sets of topic markers which can occur on each side of the topic phrase.</content></text>
<text show="swTopicYesWordEitherYes"><content> All of the topic markers may occur on either side of the topic phrase.</content></text>
</p>
<example show="swTopicMarkerYes">
